You are helping me build a capstone cybersecurity project.

PROJECT: Zero Trust Policy Enforcement and Automated Misconfiguration
Remediation System for Kubernetes.

WHAT WE ARE BUILDING:
A Kubernetes-native controller that continuously audits RBAC and
NetworkPolicy configurations against a formal Zero Trust baseline,
classifies violations by risk level, automatically remediates low-risk
violations, and escalates high-risk ones for human review.

SCOPE:
- In scope: RBAC auditing (RBAC-001 to RBAC-005), NetworkPolicy auditing
  (NP-001 to NP-003), automated remediation, violation classification,
  metrics collection, audit trail
- Out of scope: mTLS enforcement, replacing OPA/Kyverno, node-level security,
  pod security standards

TECH STACK:
- Language: Go
- Kubernetes client: controller-runtime
- CRD tooling: Kubebuilder + controller-gen
- Controller pattern: Reconciliation controller (not admission controller)
- Data storage: In-memory Policy Store + ConfigMap audit log
- Metrics: Prometheus via client_golang
- Test environment: minikube

PROJECT STRUCTURE:
- docs/architecture.md        — full system design and component specs
- docs/remediation-model.md   — violation types, risk levels, decision matrix
- docs/threat-model.md        — STRIDE analysis, trust boundaries, limitations
- docs/evaluation-plan.md     — metrics definitions and test scenarios
- docs/roadmap.md             — phased deliverables
- baseline/                   — ZeroTrustPolicy CRD YAML
- audit-engine/               — audit loop and detector modules
- remediation-engine/         — decision engine and autofix logic
- controller/                 — main controller loop and reconciler
- crds/                       — CRD definitions
- manifests/                  — test RBAC and NetworkPolicy YAMLs
- evaluations/                — test scenario scripts and results

MY CODING LEVEL:
Beginner. I understand concepts but am not fluent in Go syntax.

INSTRUCTIONS FOR ALL CODE YOU WRITE:
- Write complete, working implementations — never stubs or placeholders
- Add inline comments explaining what each block does and why
- When making an architectural decision, explain the tradeoff in a comment
- Flag anything with a comment marked // DEFENSE NOTE: that I need to
  understand and be able to explain during my capstone defense
- Follow the decision matrix in docs/remediation-model.md exactly
- Never auto-remediate anything outside the permitted autofix list
- Always write idempotent remediation actions
- Always serialize pre-remediation state before any API write
- Use structured JSON logging (zerolog or zap)
- Prefer readable code over clever code — this will be read by evaluators
